title: For Sale:  2001 Llama Max-1 .45ACP 1911 Government Model
location: Downtown El Paso, El Paso, Texas
postcontent:
2001 Llama Max-1 .45 ACP 1911-A1 clone. This gun is utterly reliable, soft-shooting, and surprisingly accurate. It's no Kimber or STI, but it'll out perform a Rock Island (both in terms of accuracy and reliability) any day of the week. It features a grip safety, thumb safety, and a firing pin safety (similar to series 80, but disengaged by the grip safety instead of the trigger). Blued finish is at least 95% in tact. All parts are original factory parts. Price includes one 8-round magazine, one 7-round steel magazine, Plano hard case, and two boxes (88 rounds) of ammo.  I am the second owner.

About the manufacturer: Llama-Gabilondo y Cia S.A. was a Spanish firearms manufacturer founded in 1904. Although Llama produced several 1911 variants over the years, the Max-1 was Llamas equivalent to the Colt Government model. This conformed more closely to the Colt 1911-A1 than any previous Llama, and removed some of the traditional Llama features such as the ventilated rib. However the slimmer mainspring housing from the earlier Llama IX-C was retained, a move considered by smaller-handed shooters to give this model superior handling qualities. The Max-1 was first introduced in 1995 and was produced until 2005 when Llama finally closed its doors.

Compatibility:

The following standard 1911 parts will fit with no modifications required:

Recoil spring, guide rod, recoil spring plug, firing pin stop, magazine, hammer, hammer strut, hammer pin, thumb safety, sear, sear pin.

The following standard parts fit with some minor modification:

Barrel bushing, barrel, firing pin, magazine catch, grip safety, slide stop, trigger, sear spring, disconnector

title: For Sale:  1965 Browning A5 Sweet Sixteen (Rare version)
location: Garner - White Oak, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent:
For sale is a mint/like new European model A5 sweet sixteen, manufactured in 1965 in Belgium. The reason it is rare is that it was manufactured specifically for the European market, purchased in Germany and brought back to the US (my grandfather bought it from a military friend of his who bought it new while he was overseas). The differences are subtle, however, with that said I have NEVER seen another one like it for sale online, and I have done a lot of research on it. It took many forum posts and talking to people much wiser than I to even learn it was a European model. The differences are that it doesn't have all the extra engravings on the receiver (only has "Sweet Sixteen" on it) and it has factory installed sling swivels (might also be a different type/color wood than usual, but that's only speculation on my end). Also had a knowledgeable seeming employee at Cabela's look at it. While he was a little stumped by it as well he believed it to be a FN High Grade Lightweight Series model based on the serial, but he hadn't seen one without the receiver engravings and factory sling swivels before.

A few specs:
-Serial number: 15188/65 (65 denotes the year, first 5 numbers are the actual serial)
-Fixed Skeet choke (**$ marking on barrel)
-27" vent rib, Acier special barrel
-Does have the speed loader function (my favorite Browning feature)

This gun was new in box, and was unfired until a couple years ago. I can personally account for every round it has ever seen, 3 boxes (75 rounds total). You can even still see some of the factory grease in the action. Shoots/cycles perfectly, remarkable how a 50 year old gun performs just as well as modern guns. I still have the original box, exterior is ok, styrofoam on the inside is pretty bad/almost gone but again, it is a 50 year old box. All that to say, yes I am asking a premium price for it ($1350 OBO), but I believe it to be a premium gun.

I have some more pictures posted in an album here: http://imgur.com/a/8F11w (can only upload one picture on here for some reason). Let me know if you have any questions about it. Thanks for looking.

title: For Sale:  Walther GSP/OSP set, early versions
location: Far NE IL, Illinois, United States
postcontent:
Price is for the GSP OSP early models "set" of the original Walther OSP in 22s and the original (first version) Walther GSP in .22lr.  Ideal for the Walther collector who wants the guns, and is not so concerned about whether the box is there or not.  Also, ideal for actual use.  The more recent Walther OSP are not as accurate or as good.  The more recent GSP are about equal in accuracy and function.  These guns are in the upper left of the image shown.  The First 2 image are the GSP with a 5 and 10 rd magazine, the third is the OSP.

Important note:  some have said the Armslist email system is NOT forwarding inquiries.  If you receive no response within a day, please email directly at REDACTED, or start by emailing directly.

The OSP is not quite the first "version" of this gun, as there are some earlier ones that are slightly different.  The GSP is the first commercial version.  There were a few prototypes before this which were similar, but were one of a kind and not sold commercially.

The OSP, and its follow-on the GSP, are derived from the first really successful "assault weapon", the Mauser C96.  The OSP increased the modular nature, the GSP was a further major jump in that modular character.

The first OSP modules do not interchange with any of the later OSP modules.  Some of the first GSP modules interchange (upper section) but with need for some recutting of the grip.  The trigger group interchanges, but not easily.  The magazines are a partial match.  The 10" GSP barrel can be used with this GSP version, but not with the OSP.

Later model GSP and OSP also are available.  Please note, these guns are assault weapons in some states or towns.  Be sure they can be shipped to you.

Also available, for $3400, is the Walther GSP in nickel in .22 and 32.  This is the 5th version of the GSP, with the grip secured by a bolt below the frame.  This is a unique set, including nickel plated weights.  The nickel guns in general are rare in the USA.  With the nickel weights, it may be one of a kind.

Other OSP and GSP are available as well.  Prices range from about 900 to $1600 depending on the gun.  The OSP and GSP in this set also are available individually, rather than as a set.

Also available is a complete Hammerli SIG P240 set in all 3 calibers, with SN matched box for the .38 gun.   (P240 in .32 only also available, but not pictured.  Looks very similar to the .38).  This set also is illustrated.

Overall condition, all guns mechanically are excellent. Cosmetics are near perfect, but it is not NIB and has had moderate use.  The grip with the gun is the original Mornini, which was used in many of these guns from the factory.  Size is large, but note the Morini grips are designed for longish fingers.  The palm shelf has been recut on this gun, usually needed on the Morini grips to allow them to fit properly.

The guns have had enough use to be past the break-in period for both mechanical smoothness, and accuracy.

Please note, in a few towns or states, this gun may be classified as an assault weapon due to some technical details of the barrel and magazine

Additional guns also are available, including

title: For Sale:  Beretta 92 Elite 9mm
postcontent: Up for sale is this slightly used Beretta 92G Elite Brigadier in the ever popular 9 mm. When you think of the fire arms company that has been around for a long time no other company can top the Beretta company. The company has been manufacturing arms and firearms since the 1500s that's a long time. The model 92 was one of the first widely adopted semi automatic pistols used by Law Enforcement agencies. It was also the second semi automatic sidearm selected by the united states military. And if it's good enough for our troops it's pretty safe to say it's good enough for us civilians. But, like all models there needs to be a time for upgrades and the Beretta 92G is exactly the upgrades needed for the Beretta 92. This version of the Beretta 92 features a stainless steel barrel, a heavy duty slide with front and rear serrations, dovetail sights, and an upgraded trigger. Anybody who has shot a regular Beretta 92 knows that the trigger has a lot of take up and at first can be a little sloppy well the Beretta 92G solved all of those problems, this trigger is light short and has little take up when in single action mode. This Beretta comes and it's almost new configuration it has the the hard plastic case, two mags, and the original lock from the factory. The original 92G Elite does not have a rail under the frame seen in the second generation brigadiers. This gun is in overall excellent condition.
